Diving Into Rust Generics
Tutorial

Diving Into Rust Generics

5 steps

In this short tutorial, you’ll learn how to use generics to define functions, structs, enums, and traits that can operate on many different types while still leveraging Rust’s strict compile-time safety. Once you get the basics, you will learn how to restrict your generic types using trait bounds.

Let's learn!

For technical help on the StackUp platform & tutorial-related questions, join our Discord, to ask your question.
Join us on Discord

Helpful prior knowledge

  • Recommended to have finished Speedrun Rust.
  • Recommended to have finished some Rust Basics tutorials.
  • A working Rust installation to run the examples. For instructions, head to https://rustup.rs/ and follow the platform-specific instructions. Otherwise, you can use the Rust Playground at https://play.rust-lang.org..

Learning Outcomes

You will be able to:

  • Explain the advantages of generics
  • Reduce duplicated code logic through generics.
  • Restrict the type parameters of functions, methods, and custom types using trait bounds.

Tutorial Steps

Total steps: 5

  • Step 1: An Example Problem Before Learning Generics

    Consider the following code example.

    struct Point {
    x: u64,
    y: u64
}

fn main() {
    let point = Point { x: 0, y: 0 };
    println!("x = {}, y = {}", point.x, point.y);
}
    Rust

    At first glance, the struct Point seems to have no issues with how it was used. However, the types of the struct fields, x and y, are constrained only to the u64 type.

    One solution to consider is to create another struct of a different name. The name can be related to what types are for the struct fields e.g. f64. A screenshot of the code below on the Rust Playground shows such a solution.

    However, you might have realised by now that such a solution also brings problems. It introduces more boilerplate code, duplicates similar code, and it might even affect readability,

    Rust has a solution for it called generics. Let's head to the next step to understand what generics are.

  • Step 2: Basic Examples Of Generics with Types

    To understand what generics are, it comes from the idea that one can have a generalised definition of a type. It acts as a label or a representation of what types can be passed over to e.g. function parameters, struct fields, enumeration variants. As long as the compiler can infer what was passed in, it's considered valid code.

    Remember from step 1 that the issue about the example structs is code duplication. Generics solve that problem by adding a representation of a generic type. This can be done by just doing the following syntax like the code example below.

    struct Point<T> {
    x: T,
    y: T
}

fn main() {
    let pointu64 = Point { x: 0 as u64, y: 0 };
    let pointf64 = Point { x: 2.5 as f64, y: 3.5 };
    println!("x = {}, y = {}", pointu64.x, pointu64.y);
    println!("x = {}, y = {}", pointf64.x, pointf64.y);
}
    Rust

    From the above code example, there is a generic type labeled as T (enclosed within left and right angled brackets <>). Because of the generic type, it solves the problem of duplicated code. You can see that both variables, pointu64 and pointf64, use the same Point struct proving the convenience of generics. The screenshot below shows the output of the code using Rust Playground.

    But that was just a basic example. Let's try using another type on one of the struct fields making each struct field's types different from each other.

    struct Point<T> {
    x: T,
    y: T
}

fn main() {
    let pointu64 = Point { x: 0 as u64, y: 0 as u32 };
    let pointf64 = Point { x: 2.5 as f64, y: 3.5 as f32 };
    println!("x = {}, y = {}", pointu64.x, pointu64.y);
    println!("x = {}, y = {}", pointf64.x, pointf64.y);
}
    Rust

    The code will not compile as shown from the screenshot below.

    The first error says "expected `u64`, found `u32`" and the second error says "expected `f64`, found `f32`". That is because the generic type T was passed on to both of the struct fields. This means both fields, x and y, should be of the same type since both of the fields were passed the same generic type e.g. if x is u64, then y should be u64 as well, vice versa.

    The solution for the problem of passing multiple types with generics, is to add a new generic type, for example, a generic type called U. You can actually change T or U to any letter or word as long as it's not a reserved keyword. Most of the examples are based on convention or other examples.

    The code example below shows that the struct, Point, now has a new generic type alongside generic type T.

    struct Point<T, U> {
    x: T,
    y: U
}

fn main() {
    let point1 = Point { x: 0 as u64, y: 0 as u32 };
    let point2 = Point { x: 2.5 as f64, y: 3.5 as f32 };
    println!("x = {}, y = {}", point1.x, point1.y);
    println!("x = {}, y = {}", point2.x, point2.y);
}
    Rust

    The code compiles without issues as shown from the screenshot below.

  • Step 3: Basic Examples of Generics with Enums

    Before we get into how generics are used in functions, let's make a little detour. Generics with enums are no different than generics with structs. The only difference is that enum variants serve as containers of types or values including generic types, thus are useful for pattern matching on enum variants and the contained values.

    Syntax is similar as well as shown from the code below

    enum Switches<T> {
    On(T),
    Off(T),
    Maybe,
    Left(i32),
    Right(i32)
}

fn main() {
    let turn_on = Switches::On(32);
    let turn_off = Switches::Off(3.5);
    match turn_on {
        Switches::On(val) => println!("It's turned on with a value of {}", val),
        _ => eprintln!("Nothing is turned on?")
    };
    match turn_off {
        Switches::Off(val) => println!("It's turned off with a value of {}", val),
        _ => eprintln!("Nothing is turned off?")
    };
}
    Rust

    The output of the code is shown by the screenshot below.

    Enums can also have multiple generic types. However, when declaring enums as variable types, the generic types should be explicitly defined. The code example below now shows that the types of the variables are explicitly defined, and the types to be passed on for the Switches enum are explicitly stated.

    enum Switches<T, U> {
    On(T),
    Off(U),
    Maybe,
    Left(i32),
    Right(i32)
}

fn main() {
    let turn_on: Switches<i32, f32> = Switches::On(32);
    let turn_off: Switches<f32, f64> = Switches::Off(3.5);
    match turn_on {
        Switches::On(val) => println!("It's turned on with a value of {}", val),
        _ => eprintln!("Nothing is turned on?")
    };
    match turn_off {
        Switches::Off(val) => println!("It's turned off with a value of {}", val),
        _ => eprintln!("Nothing is turned off?")
    };
}
    Rust

    The advantage of this explicitness not only avoids confusion but also allows for flexibility. You can see that the two variables have different types passed as their generic types; for example, the turn_on variable of the enum Switches has a generic type T that is i32 and a generic type U that is f32. 

  • Step 4: Bounds Using Generics and Limitations

    How about generics in functions? Consider the code example below.

    fn add_values<T>(a: T) -> T {
    a
}

fn main() {
    let sum = add_values(10);
    println!("The total is {}.", sum);
}
    Rust

    At first, you realise this works because there is only one parameter. But if we add more parameters and add them together like the code example below,

    fn add_values<T>(a: T, b: i32) -> T {
    a + b
}

fn main() {
    let sum = add_values(10, 10);
    println!("The total is {}.", sum);
}
    Rust

    The code will not compile as you can see from an error message that suggests a solution as shown by the screenshot below.

    The solution is to restrict the type parameter of the generic type T with a trait called Add. If you can recall correctly, traits are defined as shared behavior of types in Rust. For example, both the u32 and i32 types are different types of integer types. But both have implemented the Add trait. Therefore, if we proceed following the suggestion of the compiler error message, any value passed to the first parameter must have a type that implements the Add trait. You are now setting something called a bound or trait bound.

    fn add_values<T: std::ops::Add<i32, Output = T>>(a: T, b: i32) -> T {
    a + b
}

fn main() {
    let sum = add_values(10, 10);
    println!("The total is {}.", sum);
}
    Rust

    But why not std::ops::Add<T, Output = T> ? That's because the second parameter is of type i32 and the restriction of the generic should also follow that the value passed is within the type i32. Let's change the second parameter to a generic type T. The code now looks like the one below.

    fn add_values<T: std::ops::Add<T, Output = T>>(a: T, b: T) -> T {
    a + b
}

fn main() {
    let sum = add_values(10, 10);
    println!("The total is {}.", sum);
}
    Rust

    Now, you realise why the previous code example with the second parameter as type i32 will not allow you to set a generic type signature std::ops::Add<T, Output = T>. That's because the Add trait can only operate on the same type. Remember, in step 2, you have noticed that a generic type means that all types that are passed on to the generic type should be of the same type. Based on this knowledge, the code below will not compile.

    fn add_values<T: std::ops::Add<T, Output = T>>(a: T, b: T) -> T {
    a + b
}

fn main() {
    let sum = add_values(10, 10.0);
    println!("The total is {}.", sum);
}
    Rust

    Because the first and second parameters are not of the same type—the first parameter's value is an integer, and the second parameter's value is a float.

    Unfortunately, these are some limitations of generics–you cannot exhaustively consider all concrete and primitive types. Consider the code example below. The code will not compile.

    fn add_values<T: std::ops::Add<T, Output = T>, U: std::ops::Add<U, Output = U>>(a: T, b: T) -> u64 {
    a + b as T
}

fn main() {
    let sum = add_values::<u64, f64>(10, 10.0);
    println!("The total is {}.", sum);
}
    Rust

    Even though we know we can perform type conversions from f64 to any integer like the code example below,

    fn main() {
    let f64_val = 10.5 as f64;
    println!("An f64 value of {}.", f64_val);
    let f64_to_u64 = f64_val as u64;  // This will be converted to 10 since it's not an integer.
    println!("An f64 to u64 value of {}.", f64_to_u64);
}
    Rust

    the compiler cannot correctly infer the type from a generic type even if the return type is an explicit type e.g. u64.

    Although, calling it a "limitation" is inaccurate, the correct explanation for this is, these are more of types being constrained by their trait definitions.

    You can also add more trait bounds to your functions e.g. a type that has a trait that implements the Debug trait, the Sub trait and the Add trait. For example, the code below will not compile because the function my_add lacks a trait to bind with, a trait that allows debug printing.

    fn my_add<T: std::ops::Add<Output = T>>(a: T, b: T) -> T {
    println!("a = {:?}", a);
    a + b
}

fn main() {
    let (a, b) = (10, 124);
    let sum = my_add(a, b);
}
    Rust

    The fix is to add another trait bound with the Debug trait. The syntax is T: std::ops::Add<Output = T> + std::fmt::Debug as shown by the code below.

    fn my_add<T: std::ops::Add<Output = T> + std::fmt::Debug>(a: T, b: T) -> T {
    println!("a = {:?}", a);
    a + b
}

fn main() {
    let (a, b) = (10, 124);
    let sum = my_add(a, b);
}
    Rust

    The + sign implies that the generic type should implement the following traits.

    To add a little bit of challenge, fix the code below by adding a trait bound.

    fn clandestine_opts<T: std::ops::Add<Output = T> + std::fmt::Debug>(a: T, b: T) -> T {
    println!("a = {:?}", a);
    a - b;
    a + b
}

fn main() {
    let (a, b) = (10, 124);
    let sum = clandestine_opts(a, b);
}
    Rust

    Share your solutions and what you think about generics as a feature in Rust that you might have not experienced in other languages.

  • Step 5: Stacking It Up!

    Congratulations on finishing this short tutorial! 🎉 You have learned the basics of Rust generics. By learning how to define and use generics with functions, structs, and traits, you've unlocked one of Rust's most powerful tools for building efficient and scalable software. Keep practicing, and soon, these patterns will become second nature.
